  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of access to safe WASH services for displacement-affected communities in Kunduz Province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed project will target conflict-affected communities in Chardara, Qala-i-Zal and Dasti-Archi Districts of Kunduz Province through provision of adequate and sustainable Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services at household and community-level. The project aims to improve access to safe water and sanitation facilities as well as hygiene items to the vulnerable households in underserved communities. The response covers a critical gap in hard-to-reach areas by providing or expanding existing WASH facilities in conflict affected communities. In addition, communities hosting IDPs or Afghan returnees whose WASH facilities are overstretched will be supported though WASH services. The project will be directly implemented by the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC), continuing recent interventions in these areas (Covid-19 response). The project is aligned with the AHF Allocation Response Strategy 5th RA and has been coordinated through relevant fora, notably the Afghanistan WASH Cluster.

Targeting 1,650 vulnerable households (11,550 individuals &#x2013; 5,659 males 5,891 female) in Kunduz Province, NRC proposes to construct 3 new solar water supply system and rehabilitate/upgrade 33 existing water sources (boreholes and dug wells) through contractual services. In addition, 180 vulnerable families will be supported though conditional cash assistance for household latrine construction. Non-food items (NFI) hygiene kits and handwashing drums will be provided though in-kind distribution to the targeted households. All of the WASH project hard interventions will be complemented with soft component of hygiene promotion. The hygiene promotion session will be specifically focusing on prevention of COVID-19.

NRC will ensure that the cash-based programming under this component will follow both NRC&#x2019;s Standard Operating Procedures (SoPs) and the Cash and Voucher Working Group&#x2019;s (CVWG) recommendations on cash delivery mechanisms.</narrative>
  </description>
